p]]\n|}\n\n==Career statistics==\n''Statistics accurate as of 18 February''  ''2020''<ref>[http://superkoora.com/en/players/match_stats/350/competition:6 SuperKoora - Hassan Haidous - Matches & Stats - Qatar Stars League - All Seasons]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<sup>[[#notes gs1|1]]</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup<sup>[[#notes gs2|2]]</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental<sup>[[#notes gs3|3]]</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"15\"|[[Sadd Sports Club|Al-Sadd]]\n|rowspan=\"15\" valign=\"center\"|[[Qatar Stars League|QSL]]\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Qatar Stars League|2006\u201307]]\n|8||0||2||0||0 ||0 ||0 ||0 ||10 ||0\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Qatar Stars League|2007\u201308]]\n|16||2||2 ||0 ||0 ||0 || 1||0 || 19||2\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Qatar Stars League|2008\u201309]]\n|15||2||2 ||0 || 1|| 1|| 2|| 0||20||3\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Qatar Stars League|2009\u201310]]\n|15||6||1 ||1 || 2||2 || 5||0 || 23||9\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Qatar Stars League|2010\u201311]]\n|18||1||1 ||0 || 1||1 || 14|| 1|| 34||3\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Qatar Stars League|2011\u201312]]\n|13||2||2 ||0 ||1 ||0 || 0||0 || 16||2\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Qatar Stars League|2012\u201313]]\n|22||5||5 ||1 || 1||0|| 0|| 0|| 28||6\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Qatar Stars League|2013\u201314]]\n|24||5||4 ||2 ||5 ||1 || 9|| 0|| 42||8\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Qatar Stars League|2014\u201315]]\n|23||11||4 ||3 || 1||0 || 10|| 3|| 38||17\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Qatar Stars League|2015\u201316]]\n|25||12|| 4|| 4|| 1|| 0|| 1|| 0|| 31||16\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Qatar Stars League|2016\u201317]]\n|19||7|| 5|| 3|| 0|| 0|| 1|| 0|| 25||10\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Qatar Stars League|2017\u201318]]\n|21||12|| 4|| 1|| 1|| 0|| 6|| 0|| 32||13\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Qatar Stars League|2018\u201319]]\n|20||10|| 3|| 0|| 0|| 0|| 9|| 0|| 32||10\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Qatar Stars League|2019\u201320]]\n|13||7|| 2|| 0|| 1|| 0|| 11|| 6|| 27||13\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!252||82||41||15 ||15 ||5 ||69||10 || 377||112\n|}\n<div id=\"notes gs1\"></div><sup>1</sup><small>Includes [[Emir of Qatar Cup]] and [[Qatar Crown Prince Cup]].</small>\n<div id=\"notes gs2\"></div><sup>2</sup><small>Includes [[Sheikh Jassem Cup]].</small> and [[Qatari Stars Cup]].</small>\n<div id=\"notes gs3\"></div><sup>3</sup><small>Includes [[AFC Champions League]] and [[FIFA Club World Cup]].</small>\n<!-- NOTE: when updating stats, update the infobox too! -->\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;Al Sadd\n*[[Qatar Stars League]] (3): [[2006\u201307 Qatar Stars League|2006\u201307]], [[2012\u201313 Qatar Stars League|2012\u201313]], [[2018\u201319 Qatar Stars League|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Emir of Qatar Cup]] (4): 2007, 2014, 2015, 2017\n*[[Qatar Crown Prince Cup]] (4): 2007, 2008, 2017, 2020\n*[[Sheikh Jassem Cup]] (4): 2007, 2014, 2017, 2019\n*[[Qatari Stars Cup]] (1): 2010\n*[[AFC Champions League]] (1): [[2011 AFC Champions League|2011]]\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]] third place: [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup|2011]]\n\n===International===\n;Qatar\n*[[AFC Asian Cup]] (1): [[2019 AFC Asian Cup|2019]]\n*[[Gulf Cup of Nations]] (1): [[2014 Gulf Cup of Nations|2014]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Qatar Football Association]] Most Promising Player (1): 2008<ref>[http://forum.kooora.com/f.aspx?t=9756891 Interview with Al-Haydos (Arabic)]</ref>\n* Estad Doha Qatar Player of the Year (1): 2014<ref>[http://www.kooora.com/?n=374911&pg=1&o=n3027072 Al-Haydos chosen as Best Qatari Player of 2014 (Arabic)]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cdn.alkass.net/news_details.aspx?news_id=81901 |title=\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u062d\u0629: \u0627\u0644\u0647\u064a\u062f\u0648\u0633 \u0623\u0641\u0636\u0644 \u0644\u0627\u0639\u0628 \u0641\u064a 2014 |access-date=2015-01-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106030410/http://cdn.alkass.net/news_details.aspx?news_id=81901 |archive-date=2015-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Qatar Football Association]] Player of the Year (1): 2015<ref>[http://www.gulf-times.com/Sport/192/details/440567/Laudrup,-al-Haydos-win-top-honours-at-the-QFA-Awards Laudrup, al-Haydos win top honours at the QFA Awards]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=50em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.hassan11.com Hassan Al Haydos Fan Website]\n* {{NFT player|pid=27516}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090215010650/http://al-saddclub.com/output/page2.asp Official Al Sadd Sports Club website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120403000859/http://www.qsl.com.qa/Users/Players/PlayersDetails.aspx?pregno=5321&clubid=9&p=12&s=-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,9,-1,11,-1,-1,14, Profile at QSL.com.qa]\n*[http://kooora.com/?n=130788&obj=3027072 \u0627\u0644\u0647\u064a\u062f\u0648\u0633 \u0644\u0627\u0639\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0637\u0631\u064a:\u0639\u0648\u062f\u062a\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0645\u0646\u062a\u062e\u0628 \u0623\u0641\u0636\u0644 \u0645\u0643\u0627\u0641\u0623\u0629 \u0647\u0630\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0645 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0632\u0639\u064a\u0645 \u0633\u064a\u062d\u0642\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0642\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u064a\u0648\u064a (Interview)] {{in lang|ar}}\n\n{{Al Sadd SC squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Qatar Squads\n|bg=#660033\n|fg=white\n|bordercolor=white\n|list1=\n{{Qatar Squad 2011 AFC Asian Cup}}\n{{Qatar squad 2015 AFC Asian Cup}}\n{{Qatar squad 2019 AFC Asian Cup}}\n{{Qatar squad 2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haydos, Hassan Al}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Qatari footballers]]\n[[Category:Qatar international footballers]]\n[[Category:Al Sadd SC players]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n[[Category:2011 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:People from Doha]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:AFC Asian Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Qatar]]\n[[Category:2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n", "name_user": "Elspamo4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClub career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hassan_Al-Haydos"}
{"title_page": "Mary Laurene Browne", "text_new": "{{short description|Liberian catholic sister, educator}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mary Laurene Browne\n| image       = Mary Laurene Browne.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|February 26, 1944}}\n| birth_place = [[Maryland County, Liberia]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Alvernia University]]\n| title       = Sis. and President of Stella Maris Polytechnic University\n| mother      = \n| father      = \n}}\n'''Mary Laurene Browne''' (born February 26, 1944) is a renowned catholic sister, an educator and president of [[Stella Maris Polytechnic University]] in Monrovia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberianobserver.com/news/sis-mary-laurene-browne-clocks-72/|title=Sis. Mary Laurene Browne Clocks 72|last=Admin|first=Webmaster|date=2015-02-26|website=Liberian Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gnnliberia.com/2016/09/17/gnn-personality-profile-sis-mary-laurene-browne-woman-virtues/|title=GNN Personality Profile: Sister Mary Laurene Browne \u2013 A Woman Of Virtues|last=Brooks|first=Cholo|date=2016-09-17|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> She is also the author of many textbooks and other publications.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201705240879.html|title=Liberia: Sister Laurene Memorializes Angie Brooks With a Biography|date=May 23, 2017|work=allAfrica|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Browne|first=Mary Laurene|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_star_from_Suehn.html?id=8OtMAQAAIAAJ|title=A star from Suehn|last2=College|first2=Bishop John Collins Teachers|date=2001|publisher=Bishop John Collins Teachers College, Don Bosco Polytechnic|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMary Laurene Browne was born in Gadetarbo Chiefdom, [[Maryland County]] to Mr. and Mrs. David A. T. Browne and Elizabeth Toe. She developed the nickname \"Little Mary\" by her parents who predeceased her. Her parents divorced when she was six years old.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBrowne first attended the African Methodist Episcopal Parish Day School (AME), and later enrolled at Our Lady of Fatima High school in Maryland County.<ref name=\":0\"/> After graduating from high school, she traveled to the United States, where she attended [[Alvernia University]]. Upon the completion of her college education at Alvernia, she entered the Bernadine Franciscan Sisters Convert in [[Reading, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browne, Mary Laurene}}\n[[Category:Liberian people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Liberian catholic sister, educator}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mary Laurene Browne\n| image       = Mary Laurene Browne.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|February 26, 1944}}\n| birth_place = [[Maryland County, Liberia]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Alvernia University]]\n| title       = Sis. and President of Stella Maris Polytechnic University\n| mother      = \n| father      = \n}}\n'''Mary Laurene Browne''' (born February 26, 1944) is a renowned catholic sister, an educator and president of [[Stella Maris Polytechnic University]] in Monrovia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberianobserver.com/news/sis-mary-laurene-browne-clocks-72/|title=Sis. Mary Laurene Browne Clocks 72|last=Admin|first=Webmaster|date=2015-02-26|website=Liberian Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gnnliberia.com/2016/09/17/gnn-personality-profile-sis-mary-laurene-browne-woman-virtues/|title=GNN Personality Profile: Sister Mary Laurene Browne \u2013 A Woman Of Virtues|last=Brooks|first=Cholo|date=2016-09-17|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> She is also the author of many textbooks and other publications.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201705240879.html|title=Liberia: Sister Laurene Memorializes Angie Brooks With a Biography|date=May 23, 2017|work=allAfrica|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Browne|first=Mary Laurene|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_star_from_Suehn.html?id=8OtMAQAAIAAJ|title=A star from Suehn|last2=College|first2=Bishop John Collins Teachers|date=2001|publisher=Bishop John Collins Teachers College, Don Bosco Polytechnic|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMary Laurene Browne was born in Gadetarbo Chiefdom, [[Maryland County]] to Mr. and Mrs. David A. T. Browne and Elizabeth Toe. She developed the nickname \"Little Mary\" by her parents who predeceased her. Her parents divorced when she was six years old.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBrowne first attended the African Methodist Episcopal Parish Day School (AME), and later enrolled at Our Lady of Fatima High school in Maryland County.<ref name=\":0\"/> After graduating from high school, she traveled to the United States, where she attended [[Alvernia University]]. Upon the completion of her college education at Alvernia, she entered the Bernadine Franciscan Sisters Convert in [[Reading, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Liberian people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Laurene_Browne"}
{"title_page": "Derek McInnes", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Edward McInnes\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Edward John McInnes<ref>{{Hugman|12611|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|7|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], Scotland\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=7}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] (manager)\n| youthyears1         = 1986\u20131988 | youthclubs1 =   [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]          \n| years1         = 1988\u20131995 | clubs1 =   [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]          | caps1 = 224 | goals1 = 19\n| years2         = 1995\u20132000 | clubs2 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]                            | caps2 = 52  | goals2 = 1\n| years3         = 1998      | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] (loan) | caps3 = 13  | goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 1999\u20132000 | clubs4 = [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]]                            | caps4 = 3   | goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2000\u20132003 | clubs5 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]  | caps5 = 88  | goals5 = 6\n| years6         = 2003\u20132006 | clubs6 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]                | caps6 = 74  | goals6 = 3\n| years7         = 2006\u20132007 | clubs7 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]                          | caps7 = 13  | goals7 = 1\n| years8         = 2007\u20132008 | clubs8 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]                  | caps8 = 30  | goals8 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 478\n| totalgoals     = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 2002 | nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 2007\u20132011 | managerclubs1 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n| manageryears2  = 2011\u20132013 | managerclubs2 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| manageryears3  = 2013\u2013 | managerclubs3 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n}}\n'''Edward John McInnes''' (born 5 July 1971) is a Scottish former [[Association football|football]] player who is currently the manager of [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. He featured prominently for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] during his playing career. He won two caps for the [[Scotland national football team]] while with West Bromwich.\n\nMcInnes became manager of [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] where he had been on the playing staff, in November 2007. He guided the club to promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League]] in 2009 and retained that status for two seasons. McInnes was appointed manager of [[Football League Championship]] club [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in October 2011.<ref name=\"McInnes named Bristol City boss\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15323776.stm | work= |publisher=BBC Sport | title=McInnes named Bristol City boss | date=19 October 2011}}</ref> Despite avoiding relegation in [[2011-12 Football League Championship|2011\u201312]], McInnes was sacked by Bristol City in January 2013 with the club bottom of the Championship. He was appointed [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] manager in March 2013.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career===\nMcInnes began his professional career in 1988 as a teenager at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], where he played in 259 games in all competitions over nine seasons<ref name=fston>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/morton/player.php?playerid=603|title=Morton player Derek McInnes|website=FitbaStats|date=|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> and credited the influence of assistant manager [[John McMaster (footballer, born 1955)|John McMaster]],<ref name=winner>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/aberdeen-fc/i-could-see-derek-was-a-winner-the-first-day-we-met-at-morton/|title=John McMaster: I could see Derek was a winner the first day we met at Morton|work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]]|author=Charlie Allan|date=19 October 2016|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> before moving to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], where he spent almost five years as a squad player, taking part in 52 matches for the [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] club.<ref name=fsgers>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player.php?playerid=1284|title=Rangers player Derek McInnes|website=FitbaStats|date=|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> During his time in [[Glasgow]], McInnes had a loan spell at English club [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], where he made 13 league appearances. McInnes scored four goals for Rangers, with strikes against [[FC Alania Vladikavkaz]] in the Champions League<ref>{{cite web \n| url      = http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/rangers-go-on-long-march-with-a-two-goal-cushion-petric-makes-sure-ibrox-side-have-one-of-their-more-famous-wins-1.442140| title     = Rangers go on long march with a two-goal cushion Petric makes sure Ibrox side have one of their more famous wins| publisher = Herald Scotland| date      = 7 August 1996 |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> and Hearts in the league.<ref>{{cite web |url         = http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20081126/great-goals-tynecastle-john-robertson_2241384_1464748 |title       = Great Goals & Tynecastle: John Robertso |publisher   = HeartsFC.co.uk |date        = 10 May 1997 |accessdate  = 27 March 2010 |url-status     = dead |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120313125228/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20081126/great-goals-tynecastle-john-robertson_2241384_1464748 |archivedate = 13 March 2012 |df          = dmy-all}}</ref> He also scored twice against [[Ayr United]]<ref>{{cite web | url       = http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/ayr-heads-are-held-high-after-a-hard-night-for-rangers-gascoigne-steps-in-to-score-and-spare-the-champions-blushes-1.437526| title     = Ayr heads are held high after a hard night for Rangers Gascoigne steps in to score and spare the champions' blushes | publisher = Herald Scotland | date      = 4 September 1996 |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> and Dunfermline<ref>{{cite news | url       = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rangers-cruise-to-final-1359787.html| title     = Rangers cruise to final | publisher = [[The Independent]] | date      = 22 October 1996 |accessdate=27 March 2010| location  = London| first     = David| last      = McKinney}}</ref> in Rangers' run to the [[1996 Scottish League Cup Final]], but he did not feature in the final itself. He was also briefly at French side [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]] during a season in which the club was promoted from the [[Ligue 2|second division]], although he only featured in three league matches.\n\n===West Bromwich Albion===\nMcInnes joined [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in the summer of 2000, but a [[cruciate ligament]] injury ended his season in October. He returned the following season to captain West Brom to a place in the [[Premier League]]. He also won West Brom's Goal of the Season award at the end of the promotion campaign, for his 25-yard strike against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in the [[Battle of Bramall Lane]].<ref>{{cite book | author = West Bromwich Albion Football Club | title = Official West Bromwich Albion Season Review 2001/02 | publisher = West Bromwich Albion Football Club | year = 2002 | pages = 226 & 237 | isbn = 0-9505585-7-5}}</ref>\n\nMcInnes was the first West Brom player to be sent off in the Premier League. He was dismissed in the second half of the club's first Premier League match against Manchester United at Old Trafford in August 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man Utd vs WBA|url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~17651,00.html|publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C.|date=17 August 2002|accessdate=15 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017214232/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10366~17651%2C00.html|archivedate=17 October 2009}}</ref> He played in the majority of West Brom's Premier League games during the 2002\u201303 season but was unable to prevent them from being relegated. He made 88 league appearances and scored six times for the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] club.\n\n===Dundee United===\nMcInnes joined [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 11 July 2003, and was immediately installed as team captain by manager [[Ian McCall (footballer)|Ian McCall]]. In his first full season at [[Tannadice Park|Tannadice]], McInnes missed only three league and one cup game. He helped the club to a fifth-place finish in the [[Scottish Premier League]] and scored twice\u2014his first coming in the [[Scottish Cup]] against [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]] and his second in a league match against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. After an unsteady start to the [[2004-05 in Scottish football|2004\u201305 season]], McInnes began to take control again in the centre of midfield. He then picked up an injury with a third of the season remaining but managed to return to the first team for the [[2005 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup final]] at the end of the season.<ref name=sc05>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/4586123.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 May 2005|title=Celtic 1\u20130 Dundee United|accessdate=4 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, United manager [[Craig Brewster]] announced that McInnes was free to leave the club at the end of the season, despite having a year of his contract left to run.<ref>{{cite news| date = 10 April 2006| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dundee_utd/4897128.stm | title = Tannadice trio told to leave club| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate = 28 April 2007}}</ref> He made 83 appearances for Dundee United, with four goals scored.<ref name=arab>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabarchive.co.uk/player.php?id=145|title=Derek McInnes Player Profile|website=Arab Archive|date=|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Millwall===\nOn 24 June 2006, it was announced that McInnes had finally come to an agreement to be released from his contract and he subsequently joined [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]. The then-Lions boss [[Nigel Spackman]] gave McInnes the captain's armband with the comment: \"Every Millwall player on that pitch should be a Derek McInnes.\"<ref>{{cite news| date= 3 July 2006| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dundee_utd/5113014.stm| title= Millwall complete McInnes switch| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate = 28 April 2007}}</ref> McInnes scored once during his spell with Millwall, his goal coming in a 3\u20132 defeat to Cheltenham on 26 August 2006.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/5266134.stm| title =Cheltenham 3\u20132 Millwall | publisher=BBC Sport | date= 26 August 2006 |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n===St Johnstone===\nMcInnes left Millwall on a free transfer during the January 2007 [[transfer window]], returning to Scotland to sign for [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] late on New Year's Day.<ref>{{cite news| date= 1 January 2007| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_johnstone/6223655.stm| title= Saints take McInnes from Millwall| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate = 28 April 2007}}</ref> He made his debut for the [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] club on 6 January, against [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] in the Scottish Cup at [[McDiarmid Park]].\n\n===International===\nInternational recognition came late to McInnes as he made his [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] debut on 21 August 2002, coming on as a substitute for the last ten minutes against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in a friendly. Three months later, against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], he was a substitute once again, coming on midway through the first half.<ref>{{SFA player|10070}}</ref>\n\n== Managerial career ==\n\n=== St Johnstone ===\nMcInnes was appointed manager of St Johnstone on 27 November 2007, after the previous management team of [[Owen Coyle]] and [[Sandy Stewart (Scottish footballer)|Sandy Stewart]] had departed for [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news| title= McInnes is new St Johnstone boss| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_johnstone/7113543.stm| publisher= BBC Sport | date= 27 November 2007| accessdate = 29 November 2007}}</ref> On 2 May 2009, McInnes secured promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League]] for St Johnstone, ending their seven-year stint in the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]].<ref name = \"2009 FD\">{{cite news| title= St Johnstone 3\u20131 Morton| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/8028043.stm| publisher  = BBC Sport | date = 2 May 2009| accessdate = 2 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009\u201310 close season, McInnes was linked with the managerial positions at West Bromwich Albion and [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref name = \"new contract\"/> He remained at St Johnstone, however, and in October 2009 he signed a new contract with the [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] club.<ref name = \"new contract\">{{cite news| title= McInnes extends contract in Perth | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_johnstone/8311149.stm| publisher  = BBC Sport | date= 16 October 2009| accessdate = 17 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nMcInnes was granted permission by St Johnstone to be interviewed by [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] for their managerial position, alongside former [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] manager [[Mark Robins]] and another unnamed candidate, in October 2011. His managerial record with the Perth club was 177 games in charge, where he won 71 games, drew 53 games and lost 53 games.<ref name=\"McInnes named Bristol City boss\"/>\n\n=== Bristol City ===\nMcInnes was appointed manager of Bristol City on 19 October 2011.<ref name=\"McInnes named Bristol City boss\"/> The club were adrift at the bottom of the [[Football League Championship]], but McInnes guided City to an eight-game unbeaten run that secured their league status.<ref name = \"bristol sacked\"/>\n\nOn 6 November 2012, following City's 2\u20130 loss to [[Birmingham City]], McInnes gave \u00a3300 to 17 stranded fans who had their minibus tyres slashed outside [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's Stadium]].<ref name=Slashed>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20241363|title=Bristol City's Derek McInnes gives \u00a3300 to stranded fans |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2012|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> \n\nDuring the 2012\u201313 season, Bristol City suffered a club record seven consecutive defeats.<ref name = \"bristol sacked\"/> McInnes was sacked on 12 January 2013, after a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] left the club eight points adrift of safety.<ref name = \"bristol sacked\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21001780 |title=Derek McInnes sacked by Bristol City |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 January 2013 |accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref> After being sacked by Bristol City, McInnes said that he was \"very desperate\" to succeed and that his time at Bristol City was difficult.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen boss Derek McInnes claims he was \"desperate\" to succeed after being sacked by Bristol City|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Aberdeen-boss-Derek-McInnes-claims-desperate/story-21058565-detail/story.html|publisher=Bristol Post|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509044042/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Aberdeen-boss-Derek-McInnes-claims-desperate/story-21058565-detail/story.html|archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Aberdeen ===\n\nMcInnes was appointed Aberdeen manager on 25 March 2013, with [[Tony Docherty]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20130325/dons-confirm-mcinnes-and-docherty_2212158_3121066 |title=Dons confirm McInnes and Docherty |work=www.afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen FC |date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref> He officially took charge of the team after the Dundee United match on 6 April, with outgoing manager [[Craig Brown (footballer born 1940)|Craig Brown]] taking charge of the last two games before the late-season split.<ref name = \"aberdeen appoint\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21911117 |title=Aberdeen Appoint McInnes |work= |publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref> After the final game with Brown as manager, McInnes vowed to improve the club by helping the city of Aberdeen to \"fall in love\" with its football team again.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen manager Derek McInnes seeks Pittodrie improvement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22069334|publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 April 2013|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nAberdeen remained unbeaten in September 2013, winning twice and drawing once in the league and progressing to the Quarter-Final of the League Cup with a 5\u20130 demolition of [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]. The team's excellent form earned McInnes the Manager of the Month award for September.<ref name = \"mcinnes wins\">{{cite web |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/aberdeen/242353-aberdeen-manager-derek-mcinnes-wins-manager-of-the-month-prize/|title=McInnes Wins Manager of the Month Award|work=STV |publisher=STV |date=8 October 2013 |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe club had a positive start to 2014, taking maximum points from games against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibs]]. At the end of the month [[Russell Anderson]] scored in the 94th minute to level the game at 2\u20132 and secure a point for the Dons against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] at [[Fir Park]] to keep them in second place. McInnes praised his players and believed they \"showed good determination to get something from the game.\"<ref name = \"mcinnes praise\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140125/quotes-from-the-press-room_2212158_3637938 |title=Quotes from the Press Room |work=RedWeb |publisher=Aberdeen F.C. |date=25 January 2014 |accessdate=25 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131062312/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140125/quotes-from-the-press-room_2212158_3637938 |archive-date=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was rewarded for his efforts as he picked up the Manager of the month award for February.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen: February prizes for Derek McInnes & Adam Rooney|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26663306|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> Ahead of the League Cup final, McInnes signed an extension to his contract, tying himself to the club until the summer of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boost ahead of Cup Final as management team extend stay|url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140314/boost-ahead-of-cup-final-as-management-team-extend-stay_2212158_3712780|publisher=Aberdeen Football Club Official Website|date=14 March 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714222315/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140314/boost-ahead-of-cup-final-as-management-team-extend-stay_2212158_3712780|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] won the [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final]] 4\u20132 on penalties, after a goalless draw, a success that saw them lift their first trophy in 19 years.<ref name = \"2014 league cup\">{{cite web|title=Aberdeen 0-0 Inverness CT|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26502621|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Campbell|first=Andy|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> McInnes led Aberdeen to European qualification for the first time since 2009, achieved through a third-place finish in the [[2013-14 Scottish Premiership|league campaign]]. However, McInnes was unsatisfied with the outcome when [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] beat Aberdeen 1\u20130 to take the second place. McInnes criticised the referee for ignoring the challenge when goalkeeper [[Jamie Langfield]] was fouled by [[John Sutton (footballer)|John Sutton]], which later led to the goal scored by [[Craig Reid (footballer, born 1986)|Craig Reid]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes says refereeing decision costs Dons|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27364672|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 April 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> At the end of the season, McInnes was awarded both [[PFA Scotland Manager of the Year]] and [[SFWA Manager of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes and Jonny Hayes win PFA awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27183351|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dons boss Derek McInnes wins second manager award|url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-boss-derek-mcinnes-wins-second-manager-award-1.352634|publisher=Evening Express|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505183135/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-boss-derek-mcinnes-wins-second-manager-award-1.352634|archivedate=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the 2014/15 season, Aberdeen progressed through two qualifying rounds of the [[UEFA Europa League]], including an aggregate victory against Dutch club [[FC Groningen]]. Aberdeen finished second in the [[2014\u201315 Scottish Premiership]] and again qualified for European competition. During the 2015 close season, despite mounting speculation that he was in talks to take over at Rangers, McInnes signed a new contract with the club keeping him at Pittodrie until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33112310 |title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes agrees two-year extension at Pittodrie |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2015 |accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis Aberdeen team again pushed [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] almost all the way in the [[2015\u201316 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premiership]] title race in [[2015\u201316 in Scottish football|2015\u201316]], with Celtic eventually beating Aberdeen 3\u20132 on 8 May 2016, a match which secured the league title, with only two matches remaining.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36180795 | title=Celtic 3\u20132 Aberdeen | publisher=BBC Sport | date=8 May 2016 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> Aberdeen had begun that season winning all of its first eight league matches as well.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34236944</ref>\n\nMcInnes led Aberdeen to a third straight [[2016\u201317 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premership]] runners-up spot in season [[2016\u201317 in Scottish football|2016\u201317]].  His Aberdeen side also claimed its first win at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] since September 1991, with a 2\u20131 victory on 17 May.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/aberdeen-fc/match-report-rangers-1-2-aberdeen-fc/ | title=Match Report: Rangers 1\u20132 Aberdeen | work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] | date=17 May 2017 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> McInnes led Aberdeen to both domestic cup finals in the 2016\u201317 season, losing both to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38110297 | title=SLC Final: Aberdeen 0\u20133 Celtic | publisher=BBC Sport | date=27 November 2016 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39605157 | title=SC SF: Hibernian 2\u20133 Aberdeen | publisher=BBC Sport | date=22 April 2017 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> The team went on a ten-match winning streak at [[Pittodrie Stadium|Pittodrie]], which surpassed [[Alex Ferguson]]'s Aberdeen record of nine home wins in-a-row in [[1985\u201386 Scottish Premier Division|1985\u201386]] (although not a club record).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aberdeen-boss-derek-mcinnes-guides-10160263 | title=Aberdeen boss Derek McInnes guides team to 10-in-a-row then warns Rangers: We're ready for you | work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] | date=5 April 2017 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/aberdeen-fc/aberdeen-fc-mcinnes-ferguson-halliday/ | title=Here's a look at McInnes and Fergie's records during Pittodrie win streaks | work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> He was again shortlisted for [[PFA Scotland Manager of the Year]],<ref name=\"even_Dere\">{{Cite web\n| title = Derek McInnes one of four nominees for PFA Scotland Manager of the Year\n| author = \n| work = Evening Express\n| date = 4 May 2017\n| access-date = 18 January 2020\n| url = https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/sport/football/aberdeen-fc/aberdeen-derek-mcinnes-manager-of-the-year/\n| quote = \n}}</ref> but lost out to Celtic manager [[Brendan Rodgers]].<ref>https://twitter.com/PFAScotland/status/861306575843184641</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Aberdeen granted permission for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] to speak with McInnes about becoming their manager,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40275093 |title=Aberdeen: Sunderland agree compensation for Derek McInnes |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> but he decided to stay with Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40296863 |title=Derek McInnes: Aberdeen manager and assistant Tony Docherty to stay |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> McInnes and Docherty subsequently signed a 1-year contract extension, keeping them with the ''Dons'' until the summer of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40646318 |title=Derek McInnes: Aberdeen manager and assistant Tony Docherty sign Contract Extension |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] made an approach for McInnes in December 2017 (immediately following two league games in four days between the clubs, both won by the Glasgow side)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=485845 |title=Rangers back to winning ways with comfortable victory over Aberdeen |website=ESPN|date=29 November 2017 |accessdate=8 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=rehearsal>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 1 Rangers 2: Derek McInnes remains favourite for Ibrox job despite losing dress rehearsal at Pittodrie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/12/03/aberdeen-1-rangers-2derek-mcinnes-remains-favourite-ibrox-job/|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=3 December 2017|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> but he rejected that offer as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41916201 |title=Aberdeen: Rangers target Derek McInnes to remain at Pittodrie |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcInnes was sent off by the referee for gesturing at Celtic fans during a [[2018&ndash;19 Scottish Cup]] semi-final in April 2019.<ref name = \"abuse\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47928279 |title=Aberdeen 0-3 Celtic: Derek McInnes sending-off 'down to sectarian abuse' |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> He was apparently reacting to [[sectarianism in Glasgow|sectarian]] abuse by Celtic fans, which was investigated by [[Police Scotland]].<ref name = \"abuse\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47938458 |title=Aberdeen: Police investigate Derek McInnes 'sectarian abuse' |first=Jane |last=Lewis |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 he signed a new contract with Aberdeen, until 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48951005|title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes & assistant extend contracts until 2022|date=11 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Player===\n<div style=\"font-size:95%\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Club !! Season !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Scotland\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]](88-94)<ref name=fston/><br>Greenock Morton (94-96){{efn|10 total appearances, 0 goals in [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] not included in table.}}||[[1987-88 in Scottish football|1987\u201388]]||[[Scottish Premier Division]]||2||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||2||0\n|-\n|[[1988-89 in Scottish football|1988\u201389]]||[[Scottish First Division]]||29||1||5||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||36||1\n|-\n|[[1989-90 in Scottish football|1989\u201390]]||Scottish First Division||23||1||3||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||26||1\n|-\n|[[1990-91 in Scottish football|1990\u201391]]||Scottish First Division||34||3||3||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||38||3\n|-\n|[[1991-92 in Scottish football|1991\u201392]]||Scottish First Division||42||7||2||0||1||1||colspan=2|-||45||8\n|-\n|[[1992-93 in Scottish football|1992\u201393]]||Scottish First Division||40||2||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||42||2\n|-\n|[[1993-94 in Scottish football|1993\u201394]]||Scottish First Division||16||1||0||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||18||1\n|-\n|[[1994-95 in Scottish football|1994\u201395]]||[[Scottish Second Division]]||26||3||3||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||29||3\n|-\n|[[1995-96 in Scottish football|1995\u201396]]||Scottish First Division||12||1||colspan=2|-||1||0||colspan=2|-||13||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!224!!19!!17!!0!!8!!1!!colspan=2|-!!249!!20\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]<ref name=fsgers/>||[[1995-96 in Scottish football|1995\u201396]]||Scottish Premier Division||6||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||colspan=2|-||6||0\n|-\n|[[1996-97 in Scottish football|1996\u201397]]||Scottish Premier Division||20||1||1||0||4||2||7||1||32||4\n|-\n|[[1997-98 in Scottish football|1997\u201398]]||Scottish Premier Division||0||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[1998-99 in Scottish football|1998\u201399]]||[[Scottish Premier League]]||7||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||colspan=2|-||9||0\n|-\n|[[1999-00 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000]]||Scottish Premier League||1||0||colspan=2|-||1||0||2||0||4||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!33!!1!!3!!0!!6!!2!!9!!1!!52!!4\n|-\n! colspan=3 | England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] (loan)||[[1998-99 in English football|1998\u201399]]||[[Football League First Division]]||13||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||colspan=2|-||15||0\n|-\n! colspan=3 | France\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Coupe de France]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Coupe de la Ligue]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[Toulouse F.C.|Toulouse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballdatabase.eu/fr/joueur/details/9689-derek-mcinnes |title=Derek McInnes |publisher=footballdatabase.eu |date=  |accessdate=4 November 2018 | language=fr}}</ref>||[[1999\u20132000 French Division 2|1999\u20132000]]||[[Ligue 2|French Division 2]]||3||0||2||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||6||0\n|-\n! colspan=3 | England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]||[[2000-01 in English football|2000\u201301]]||Football League First Division||14||1||0||0||4||0||colspan=2|-||18||1\n|-\n|[[2001-02 in English football|2001\u201302]]||Football League First Division||45||3||4||0||3||0||colspan=2|-||52||3\n|-\n|[[2002-03 in English football|2002\u201303]]||[[FA Premier League]]||29||2||1||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||30||2\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!88!!6!!5!!0!!7!!0!!colspan=2|-!!100!!6\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Scotland\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]<ref name=arab/>||[[2003-04 in Scottish football|2003\u201304]]||Scottish Premier League||35||1||1||1||1||0||colspan=2|-||37||2\n|-\n|[[2004-05 in Scottish football|2004\u201305]]||Scottish Premier League||27||0||3||0||3||0||colspan=2|-||33||0\n|-\n|[[2005-06 in Scottish football|2005\u201306]]||Scottish Premier League||12||2||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||13||2\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!74!!3!!4!!1!!5!!0!!colspan=2|-!!83!!4\n|-\n! colspan=3 | England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]||[[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]]||[[Football League One]]||13||1||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||15||1\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Scotland\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]||[[2006-07 in Scottish football|2006\u201307]]||Scottish First Division||16||0||4||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||21||0\n|-\n|[[2007-08 in Scottish football|2007\u201308]]||Scottish First Division||14||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||15||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!30!!0!!4!!0!!2!!0!!colspan=2|-!!36!!0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total!!478!!30!!38!!1!!30!!3!!9!!1!!555!!35\n|}\n</div>\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Managerial record===\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n|align=left|27 November 2007\n|align=left|19 October 2011\n{{WDL|177|71|53|53}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|align=left|19 October 2011\n|align=left|12 January 2013\n{{WDL|63|17|14|32}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n|align=left|7 April 2013\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|341|187|65|89}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|579|273|132|174}}\n|}\n\n==Honours and achievements==\n\n===Player===\n;Greenock Morton\n*[[Scottish Football League Second Division|Scottish Second Division]]: [[1994-95 in Scottish football|1994\u201395]]\n\n;Rangers\n*[[Scottish Premier Division]]: [[1996-97 Scottish Premier Division|1996-97]] \n*[[Scottish Cup]]: [[1998-99 Scottish Cup|1998\u201399]]\n\n;St Johnstone\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]]: [[2007-08 in Scottish football|2007\u201308]]\n\n===Manager===\n;St Johnstone\n*[[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]]: [[2008-09 in Scottish football|2008\u201309]]<ref name = \"2009 FD\"/>\n\n;Aberdeen\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final|2013\u201314]]<ref name = \"2014 league cup\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.stjohnstonefc.co.uk/playerprofile.asp?PlayerID=133 St Johnstone FC profile]\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{soccerbase (manager)|id=2113}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{PFA Scotland Manager of the Year}}\n{{SFWA Manager of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Derek McInnes managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{St Johnstone F.C. managers}}\n{{Bristol City F.C. managers}}\n{{Aberdeen F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Scottish Premier League managers}}\n{{Aberdeen F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McInnes, Derek}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paisley, Renfrewshire]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Toulouse FC players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Derek McInnes\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Derek John McInnes<ref>{{Hugman|12611|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|7|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], Scotland\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=7}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] (manager)\n| youthyears1         = 1986\u20131988 | youthclubs1 =   [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]          \n| years1         = 1988\u20131995 | clubs1 =   [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]          | caps1 = 224 | goals1 = 19\n| years2         = 1995\u20132000 | clubs2 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]                            | caps2 = 52  | goals2 = 1\n| years3         = 1998      | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] (loan) | caps3 = 13  | goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 1999\u20132000 | clubs4 = [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]]                            | caps4 = 3   | goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2000\u20132003 | clubs5 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]  | caps5 = 88  | goals5 = 6\n| years6         = 2003\u20132006 | clubs6 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]                | caps6 = 74  | goals6 = 3\n| years7         = 2006\u20132007 | clubs7 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]                          | caps7 = 13  | goals7 = 1\n| years8         = 2007\u20132008 | clubs8 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]                  | caps8 = 30  | goals8 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 478\n| totalgoals     = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 2002 | nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 2007\u20132011 | managerclubs1 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n| manageryears2  = 2011\u20132013 | managerclubs2 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| manageryears3  = 2013\u2013 | managerclubs3 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n}}\n'''Derek John McInnes''' (born 5 July 1971) is a Scottish former [[Association football|football]] player who is currently the manager of [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. He featured prominently for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] during his playing career. He won two caps for the [[Scotland national football team]] while with West Bromwich.\n\nMcInnes became manager of [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] where he had been on the playing staff, in November 2007. He guided the club to promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League]] in 2009 and retained that status for two seasons. McInnes was appointed manager of [[Football League Championship]] club [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in October 2011.<ref name=\"McInnes named Bristol City boss\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15323776.stm | work= |publisher=BBC Sport | title=McInnes named Bristol City boss | date=19 October 2011}}</ref> Despite avoiding relegation in [[2011-12 Football League Championship|2011\u201312]], McInnes was sacked by Bristol City in January 2013 with the club bottom of the Championship. He was appointed [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] manager in March 2013.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career===\nMcInnes began his professional career in 1988 as a teenager at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], where he played in 259 games in all competitions over nine seasons<ref name=fston>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/morton/player.php?playerid=603|title=Morton player Derek McInnes|website=FitbaStats|date=|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> and credited the influence of assistant manager [[John McMaster (footballer, born 1955)|John McMaster]],<ref name=winner>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/aberdeen-fc/i-could-see-derek-was-a-winner-the-first-day-we-met-at-morton/|title=John McMaster: I could see Derek was a winner the first day we met at Morton|work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]]|author=Charlie Allan|date=19 October 2016|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> before moving to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], where he spent almost five years as a squad player, taking part in 52 matches for the [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] club.<ref name=fsgers>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player.php?playerid=1284|title=Rangers player Derek McInnes|website=FitbaStats|date=|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> During his time in [[Glasgow]], McInnes had a loan spell at English club [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], where he made 13 league appearances. McInnes scored four goals for Rangers, with strikes against [[FC Alania Vladikavkaz]] in the Champions League<ref>{{cite web \n| url      = http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/rangers-go-on-long-march-with-a-two-goal-cushion-petric-makes-sure-ibrox-side-have-one-of-their-more-famous-wins-1.442140| title     = Rangers go on long march with a two-goal cushion Petric makes sure Ibrox side have one of their more famous wins| publisher = Herald Scotland| date      = 7 August 1996 |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> and Hearts in the league.<ref>{{cite web |url         = http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20081126/great-goals-tynecastle-john-robertson_2241384_1464748 |title       = Great Goals & Tynecastle: John Robertso |publisher   = HeartsFC.co.uk |date        = 10 May 1997 |accessdate  = 27 March 2010 |url-status     = dead |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120313125228/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20081126/great-goals-tynecastle-john-robertson_2241384_1464748 |archivedate = 13 March 2012 |df          = dmy-all}}</ref> He also scored twice against [[Ayr United]]<ref>{{cite web | url       = http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/ayr-heads-are-held-high-after-a-hard-night-for-rangers-gascoigne-steps-in-to-score-and-spare-the-champions-blushes-1.437526| title     = Ayr heads are held high after a hard night for Rangers Gascoigne steps in to score and spare the champions' blushes | publisher = Herald Scotland | date      = 4 September 1996 |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> and Dunfermline<ref>{{cite news | url       = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rangers-cruise-to-final-1359787.html| title     = Rangers cruise to final | publisher = [[The Independent]] | date      = 22 October 1996 |accessdate=27 March 2010| location  = London| first     = David| last      = McKinney}}</ref> in Rangers' run to the [[1996 Scottish League Cup Final]], but he did not feature in the final itself. He was also briefly at French side [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]] during a season in which the club was promoted from the [[Ligue 2|second division]], although he only featured in three league matches.\n\n===West Bromwich Albion===\nMcInnes joined [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in the summer of 2000, but a [[cruciate ligament]] injury ended his season in October. He returned the following season to captain West Brom to a place in the [[Premier League]]. He also won West Brom's Goal of the Season award at the end of the promotion campaign, for his 25-yard strike against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in the [[Battle of Bramall Lane]].<ref>{{cite book | author = West Bromwich Albion Football Club | title = Official West Bromwich Albion Season Review 2001/02 | publisher = West Bromwich Albion Football Club | year = 2002 | pages = 226 & 237 | isbn = 0-9505585-7-5}}</ref>\n\nMcInnes was the first West Brom player to be sent off in the Premier League. He was dismissed in the second half of the club's first Premier League match against Manchester United at Old Trafford in August 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man Utd vs WBA|url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~17651,00.html|publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C.|date=17 August 2002|accessdate=15 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017214232/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10366~17651%2C00.html|archivedate=17 October 2009}}</ref> He played in the majority of West Brom's Premier League games during the 2002\u201303 season but was unable to prevent them from being relegated. He made 88 league appearances and scored six times for the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] club.\n\n===Dundee United===\nMcInnes joined [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 11 July 2003, and was immediately installed as team captain by manager [[Ian McCall (footballer)|Ian McCall]]. In his first full season at [[Tannadice Park|Tannadice]], McInnes missed only three league and one cup game. He helped the club to a fifth-place finish in the [[Scottish Premier League]] and scored twice\u2014his first coming in the [[Scottish Cup]] against [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]] and his second in a league match against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. After an unsteady start to the [[2004-05 in Scottish football|2004\u201305 season]], McInnes began to take control again in the centre of midfield. He then picked up an injury with a third of the season remaining but managed to return to the first team for the [[2005 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup final]] at the end of the season.<ref name=sc05>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/4586123.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 May 2005|title=Celtic 1\u20130 Dundee United|accessdate=4 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, United manager [[Craig Brewster]] announced that McInnes was free to leave the club at the end of the season, despite having a year of his contract left to run.<ref>{{cite news| date = 10 April 2006| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dundee_utd/4897128.stm | title = Tannadice trio told to leave club| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate = 28 April 2007}}</ref> He made 83 appearances for Dundee United, with four goals scored.<ref name=arab>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabarchive.co.uk/player.php?id=145|title=Derek McInnes Player Profile|website=Arab Archive|date=|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Millwall===\nOn 24 June 2006, it was announced that McInnes had finally come to an agreement to be released from his contract and he subsequently joined [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]. The then-Lions boss [[Nigel Spackman]] gave McInnes the captain's armband with the comment: \"Every Millwall player on that pitch should be a Derek McInnes.\"<ref>{{cite news| date= 3 July 2006| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dundee_utd/5113014.stm| title= Millwall complete McInnes switch| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate = 28 April 2007}}</ref> McInnes scored once during his spell with Millwall, his goal coming in a 3\u20132 defeat to Cheltenham on 26 August 2006.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/5266134.stm| title =Cheltenham 3\u20132 Millwall | publisher=BBC Sport | date= 26 August 2006 |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n===St Johnstone===\nMcInnes left Millwall on a free transfer during the January 2007 [[transfer window]], returning to Scotland to sign for [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] late on New Year's Day.<ref>{{cite news| date= 1 January 2007| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_johnstone/6223655.stm| title= Saints take McInnes from Millwall| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate = 28 April 2007}}</ref> He made his debut for the [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] club on 6 January, against [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] in the Scottish Cup at [[McDiarmid Park]].\n\n===International===\nInternational recognition came late to McInnes as he made his [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] debut on 21 August 2002, coming on as a substitute for the last ten minutes against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in a friendly. Three months later, against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], he was a substitute once again, coming on midway through the first half.<ref>{{SFA player|10070}}</ref>\n\n== Managerial career ==\n\n=== St Johnstone ===\nMcInnes was appointed manager of St Johnstone on 27 November 2007, after the previous management team of [[Owen Coyle]] and [[Sandy Stewart (Scottish footballer)|Sandy Stewart]] had departed for [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news| title= McInnes is new St Johnstone boss| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_johnstone/7113543.stm| publisher= BBC Sport | date= 27 November 2007| accessdate = 29 November 2007}}</ref> On 2 May 2009, McInnes secured promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League]] for St Johnstone, ending their seven-year stint in the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]].<ref name = \"2009 FD\">{{cite news| title= St Johnstone 3\u20131 Morton| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/8028043.stm| publisher  = BBC Sport | date = 2 May 2009| accessdate = 2 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009\u201310 close season, McInnes was linked with the managerial positions at West Bromwich Albion and [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref name = \"new contract\"/> He remained at St Johnstone, however, and in October 2009 he signed a new contract with the [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] club.<ref name = \"new contract\">{{cite news| title= McInnes extends contract in Perth | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_johnstone/8311149.stm| publisher  = BBC Sport | date= 16 October 2009| accessdate = 17 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nMcInnes was granted permission by St Johnstone to be interviewed by [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] for their managerial position, alongside former [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] manager [[Mark Robins]] and another unnamed candidate, in October 2011. His managerial record with the Perth club was 177 games in charge, where he won 71 games, drew 53 games and lost 53 games.<ref name=\"McInnes named Bristol City boss\"/>\n\n=== Bristol City ===\nMcInnes was appointed manager of Bristol City on 19 October 2011.<ref name=\"McInnes named Bristol City boss\"/> The club were adrift at the bottom of the [[Football League Championship]], but McInnes guided City to an eight-game unbeaten run that secured their league status.<ref name = \"bristol sacked\"/>\n\nOn 6 November 2012, following City's 2\u20130 loss to [[Birmingham City]], McInnes gave \u00a3300 to 17 stranded fans who had their minibus tyres slashed outside [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's Stadium]].<ref name=Slashed>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20241363|title=Bristol City's Derek McInnes gives \u00a3300 to stranded fans |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2012|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> \n\nDuring the 2012\u201313 season, Bristol City suffered a club record seven consecutive defeats.<ref name = \"bristol sacked\"/> McInnes was sacked on 12 January 2013, after a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] left the club eight points adrift of safety.<ref name = \"bristol sacked\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21001780 |title=Derek McInnes sacked by Bristol City |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 January 2013 |accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref> After being sacked by Bristol City, McInnes said that he was \"very desperate\" to succeed and that his time at Bristol City was difficult.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen boss Derek McInnes claims he was \"desperate\" to succeed after being sacked by Bristol City|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Aberdeen-boss-Derek-McInnes-claims-desperate/story-21058565-detail/story.html|publisher=Bristol Post|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509044042/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Aberdeen-boss-Derek-McInnes-claims-desperate/story-21058565-detail/story.html|archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Aberdeen ===\n\nMcInnes was appointed Aberdeen manager on 25 March 2013, with [[Tony Docherty]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20130325/dons-confirm-mcinnes-and-docherty_2212158_3121066 |title=Dons confirm McInnes and Docherty |work=www.afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen FC |date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref> He officially took charge of the team after the Dundee United match on 6 April, with outgoing manager [[Craig Brown (footballer born 1940)|Craig Brown]] taking charge of the last two games before the late-season split.<ref name = \"aberdeen appoint\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21911117 |title=Aberdeen Appoint McInnes |work= |publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref> After the final game with Brown as manager, McInnes vowed to improve the club by helping the city of Aberdeen to \"fall in love\" with its football team again.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen manager Derek McInnes seeks Pittodrie improvement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22069334|publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 April 2013|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nAberdeen remained unbeaten in September 2013, winning twice and drawing once in the league and progressing to the Quarter-Final of the League Cup with a 5\u20130 demolition of [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]. The team's excellent form earned McInnes the Manager of the Month award for September.<ref name = \"mcinnes wins\">{{cite web |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/aberdeen/242353-aberdeen-manager-derek-mcinnes-wins-manager-of-the-month-prize/|title=McInnes Wins Manager of the Month Award|work=STV |publisher=STV |date=8 October 2013 |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe club had a positive start to 2014, taking maximum points from games against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibs]]. At the end of the month [[Russell Anderson]] scored in the 94th minute to level the game at 2\u20132 and secure a point for the Dons against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] at [[Fir Park]] to keep them in second place. McInnes praised his players and believed they \"showed good determination to get something from the game.\"<ref name = \"mcinnes praise\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140125/quotes-from-the-press-room_2212158_3637938 |title=Quotes from the Press Room |work=RedWeb |publisher=Aberdeen F.C. |date=25 January 2014 |accessdate=25 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131062312/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140125/quotes-from-the-press-room_2212158_3637938 |archive-date=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was rewarded for his efforts as he picked up the Manager of the month award for February.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen: February prizes for Derek McInnes & Adam Rooney|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26663306|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> Ahead of the League Cup final, McInnes signed an extension to his contract, tying himself to the club until the summer of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boost ahead of Cup Final as management team extend stay|url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140314/boost-ahead-of-cup-final-as-management-team-extend-stay_2212158_3712780|publisher=Aberdeen Football Club Official Website|date=14 March 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714222315/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20140314/boost-ahead-of-cup-final-as-management-team-extend-stay_2212158_3712780|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] won the [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final]] 4\u20132 on penalties, after a goalless draw, a success that saw them lift their first trophy in 19 years.<ref name = \"2014 league cup\">{{cite web|title=Aberdeen 0-0 Inverness CT|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26502621|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Campbell|first=Andy|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> McInnes led Aberdeen to European qualification for the first time since 2009, achieved through a third-place finish in the [[2013-14 Scottish Premiership|league campaign]]. However, McInnes was unsatisfied with the outcome when [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] beat Aberdeen 1\u20130 to take the second place. McInnes criticised the referee for ignoring the challenge when goalkeeper [[Jamie Langfield]] was fouled by [[John Sutton (footballer)|John Sutton]], which later led to the goal scored by [[Craig Reid (footballer, born 1986)|Craig Reid]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes says refereeing decision costs Dons|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27364672|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 April 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> At the end of the season, McInnes was awarded both [[PFA Scotland Manager of the Year]] and [[SFWA Manager of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes and Jonny Hayes win PFA awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27183351|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dons boss Derek McInnes wins second manager award|url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-boss-derek-mcinnes-wins-second-manager-award-1.352634|publisher=Evening Express|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505183135/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-boss-derek-mcinnes-wins-second-manager-award-1.352634|archivedate=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the 2014/15 season, Aberdeen progressed through two qualifying rounds of the [[UEFA Europa League]], including an aggregate victory against Dutch club [[FC Groningen]]. Aberdeen finished second in the [[2014\u201315 Scottish Premiership]] and again qualified for European competition. During the 2015 close season, despite mounting speculation that he was in talks to take over at Rangers, McInnes signed a new contract with the club keeping him at Pittodrie until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33112310 |title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes agrees two-year extension at Pittodrie |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2015 |accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis Aberdeen team again pushed [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] almost all the way in the [[2015\u201316 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premiership]] title race in [[2015\u201316 in Scottish football|2015\u201316]], with Celtic eventually beating Aberdeen 3\u20132 on 8 May 2016, a match which secured the league title, with only two matches remaining.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36180795 | title=Celtic 3\u20132 Aberdeen | publisher=BBC Sport | date=8 May 2016 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> Aberdeen had begun that season winning all of its first eight league matches as well.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34236944</ref>\n\nMcInnes led Aberdeen to a third straight [[2016\u201317 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premership]] runners-up spot in season [[2016\u201317 in Scottish football|2016\u201317]].  His Aberdeen side also claimed its first win at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] since September 1991, with a 2\u20131 victory on 17 May.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/aberdeen-fc/match-report-rangers-1-2-aberdeen-fc/ | title=Match Report: Rangers 1\u20132 Aberdeen | work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] | date=17 May 2017 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> McInnes led Aberdeen to both domestic cup finals in the 2016\u201317 season, losing both to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38110297 | title=SLC Final: Aberdeen 0\u20133 Celtic | publisher=BBC Sport | date=27 November 2016 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39605157 | title=SC SF: Hibernian 2\u20133 Aberdeen | publisher=BBC Sport | date=22 April 2017 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> The team went on a ten-match winning streak at [[Pittodrie Stadium|Pittodrie]], which surpassed [[Alex Ferguson]]'s Aberdeen record of nine home wins in-a-row in [[1985\u201386 Scottish Premier Division|1985\u201386]] (although not a club record).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aberdeen-boss-derek-mcinnes-guides-10160263 | title=Aberdeen boss Derek McInnes guides team to 10-in-a-row then warns Rangers: We're ready for you | work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] | date=5 April 2017 | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/aberdeen-fc/aberdeen-fc-mcinnes-ferguson-halliday/ | title=Here's a look at McInnes and Fergie's records during Pittodrie win streaks | work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] | accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> He was again shortlisted for [[PFA Scotland Manager of the Year]],<ref name=\"even_Dere\">{{Cite web\n| title = Derek McInnes one of four nominees for PFA Scotland Manager of the Year\n| author = \n| work = Evening Express\n| date = 4 May 2017\n| access-date = 18 January 2020\n| url = https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/sport/football/aberdeen-fc/aberdeen-derek-mcinnes-manager-of-the-year/\n| quote = \n}}</ref> but lost out to Celtic manager [[Brendan Rodgers]].<ref>https://twitter.com/PFAScotland/status/861306575843184641</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Aberdeen granted permission for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] to speak with McInnes about becoming their manager,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40275093 |title=Aberdeen: Sunderland agree compensation for Derek McInnes |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> but he decided to stay with Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40296863 |title=Derek McInnes: Aberdeen manager and assistant Tony Docherty to stay |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> McInnes and Docherty subsequently signed a 1-year contract extension, keeping them with the ''Dons'' until the summer of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40646318 |title=Derek McInnes: Aberdeen manager and assistant Tony Docherty sign Contract Extension |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] made an approach for McInnes in December 2017 (immediately following two league games in four days between the clubs, both won by the Glasgow side)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=485845 |title=Rangers back to winning ways with comfortable victory over Aberdeen |website=ESPN|date=29 November 2017 |accessdate=8 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=rehearsal>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 1 Rangers 2: Derek McInnes remains favourite for Ibrox job despite losing dress rehearsal at Pittodrie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/12/03/aberdeen-1-rangers-2derek-mcinnes-remains-favourite-ibrox-job/|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=3 December 2017|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> but he rejected that offer as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41916201 |title=Aberdeen: Rangers target Derek McInnes to remain at Pittodrie |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcInnes was sent off by the referee for gesturing at Celtic fans during a [[2018&ndash;19 Scottish Cup]] semi-final in April 2019.<ref name = \"abuse\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47928279 |title=Aberdeen 0-3 Celtic: Derek McInnes sending-off 'down to sectarian abuse' |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> He was apparently reacting to [[sectarianism in Glasgow|sectarian]] abuse by Celtic fans, which was investigated by [[Police Scotland]].<ref name = \"abuse\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47938458 |title=Aberdeen: Police investigate Derek McInnes 'sectarian abuse' |first=Jane |last=Lewis |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 he signed a new contract with Aberdeen, until 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48951005|title=Aberdeen: Derek McInnes & assistant extend contracts until 2022|date=11 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Player===\n<div style=\"font-size:95%\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Club !! Season !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Scotland\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]](88-94)<ref name=fston/><br>Greenock Morton (94-96){{efn|10 total appearances, 0 goals in [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] not included in table.}}||[[1987-88 in Scottish football|1987\u201388]]||[[Scottish Premier Division]]||2||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||2||0\n|-\n|[[1988-89 in Scottish football|1988\u201389]]||[[Scottish First Division]]||29||1||5||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||36||1\n|-\n|[[1989-90 in Scottish football|1989\u201390]]||Scottish First Division||23||1||3||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||26||1\n|-\n|[[1990-91 in Scottish football|1990\u201391]]||Scottish First Division||34||3||3||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||38||3\n|-\n|[[1991-92 in Scottish football|1991\u201392]]||Scottish First Division||42||7||2||0||1||1||colspan=2|-||45||8\n|-\n|[[1992-93 in Scottish football|1992\u201393]]||Scottish First Division||40||2||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|-||42||2\n|-\n|[[1993-94 in Scottish football|1993\u201394]]||Scottish First Division||16||1||0||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||18||1\n|-\n|[[1994-95 in Scottish football|1994\u201395]]||[[Scottish Second Division]]||26||3||3||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||29||3\n|-\n|[[1995-96 in Scottish football|1995\u201396]]||Scottish First Division||12||1||colspan=2|-||1||0||colspan=2|-||13||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!224!!19!!17!!0!!8!!1!!colspan=2|-!!249!!20\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]<ref name=fsgers/>||[[1995-96 in Scottish football|1995\u201396]]||Scottish Premier Division||6||0||0||0||colspan=2|-||colspan=2|-||6||0\n|-\n|[[1996-97 in Scottish football|1996\u201397]]||Scottish Premier Division||20||1||1||0||4||2||7||1||32||4\n|-\n|[[1997-98 in Scottish football|1997\u201398]]||Scottish Premier Division||0||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[1998-99 in Scottish football|1998\u201399]]||[[Scottish Premier League]]||7||0||2||0||colspan=2|-||colspan=2|-||9||0\n|-\n|[[1999-00 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000]]||Scottish Premier League||1||0||colspan=2|-||1||0||2||0||4||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!33!!1!!3!!0!!6!!2!!9!!1!!52!!4\n|-\n! colspan=3