eased, called ''[[Neighbours from Hell 2: On Vacation]]''. In this game, instead of being in a house, the player travels to various locations around the world. This time the player must have their caution turned to the mom of the Neighbour too, if they do not want to be caught.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120710062828/http://www.neighbours-from-hell.com/ The official website of the Neighbours from Hell series]\n*{{moby game|id=/windows/neighbors-from-hell|name=''Neighbors from Hell'' (Windows)}}\n*{{moby game|id=/neighbors-from-hell_|name=''Neighbors from Hell'' (GameCube, Xbox)}}\n*{{moby game|id=/nintendo-ds/neighbours-from-hell|name=''Neighbours from Hell'' (Nintendo DS)}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neighbours From Hell}}\n[[Category:2003 video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:GameCube games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo DS games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Strategy video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Austria]]\n[[Category:JoWooD Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:THQ Nordic games]]\n[[Category:THQ Nordic franchises]]\n[[Category:Neighbours from Hell]]\n", "name_user": "Angeldeb82", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neighbours_from_Hell"}
{"title_page": "Lake Las Vegas", "text_new": "{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Lake Las Vegas\n | image = Lake Las Vegas aerial view.jpg\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry =\n | caption_bathymetry =\n | location = [[Henderson, Nevada]]\n | type = [[Artificial lake]]\n | inflow = \n | outflow = Las Vegas Wash\n | catchment = nil\n | basin_countries = United States\n | length =\n | width =\n | area = {{convert|320|acre|abbr=on}}\n | depth =\n | max-depth =\n | volume =\n | residence_time =\n | shore = {{convert|10|mi|abbr=on}}\n | elevation = {{convert|1400|ft|abbr=on}}\n | islands = 0\n | cities = Lake Las Vegas\n | frozen =\n | reference = <ref name=lvl1>{{cite news |first=Scott |last= Dickensheets |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Is Lake Las Vegas Half Full or Half Empty? |work= [[Las Vegas Life]] |publisher= |date=November 2000 }}</ref>\n |coordinates = {{coord|36|06|07.2|N|114|55|46.2|W|display=inline}}\n |pushpin_map             = USA Nevada\n |pushpin_label_position  = \n |pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Nevada\n}}\n[[File:Lake Las Vegas 1.jpg|thumb|240px|Lake Las Vegas in 2007]]\n\n'''Lake Las Vegas''' in [[Henderson, Nevada]], refers to a {{convert|320|acre|adj=on}} [[artificial lake]] and the {{convert|3592|acre|adj=on}} developed area around the lake.<ref name=rj1/><ref name=iht1/>  The area is sometimes referred to as the ''Lake Las Vegas Resort''. It is being developed by 5 companies including Lake at Las Vegas Joint Venture LLC.<ref name=ktnv1/>\n\nThe area includes three resorts including the Aston MonteLago Village Resort, the Westin Lake Las Vegas Resort, and the Hilton Lake Las Vegas.\n\nThe dam that creates the lake is \"an earthen structure 18 stories high, {{convert|4800|ft|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|716|ft|abbr=on}} wide at its base. It contains roughly the same amount of dirt as [[Hoover Dam]] does concrete,\"<ref name=lvl1/> and was completed in 1991.<ref name=llvr1/>  The [[Las Vegas Wash]] passes under the lake and dam in pipes that require maintenance every 10 years.<ref name=RJ2080802>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= EDITORIAL: Lake Las Vegas -- dry? |url=http://www.lvrj.com/opinion/26204144.html |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |publisher= |date= 2008-08-02|accessdate=2008-08-02 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nActor [[J. Carlton Adair]] conceived Lake Las Vegas around 1967 as ''Lake Adair''. At the time he purchased the land and water rights. In 1987, [[Ronald Boeddeker]] acquired {{convert|2000|acre|abbr=on}} from the US Government when Adair went bankrupt.<ref name=rj1>{{cite news|title=Lake Las Vegas properties change hands|last=Knightly |first=Arnold M.|date=2008-01-09|accessdate = 2008-01-13|pages=1D, 4D|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/lake-las-vegas-properties-change-hands}}</ref><ref name=iht1>{{cite news|title=Lakeside resort trumps Las Vegas | url= http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/01/09/america/relake.php |last= Vaucher|first=Andr\u00e9a R.|date=2008-01-10|accessdate = 2008-01-13|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nThe property was acquired by Transcontinental Properties in 1990. In 1995, [[Henry Gluck]], the former chairman and chief executive officer of [[Caesars World]], became the co-Chairman of Transcontinental Properties.<ref name=\"julietamaki\">Julie Tamaki, [http://articles.latimes.com/1999/aug/01/realestate/re-61511 Viva Luxe Vegas], ''The Los Angeles Times'', August 01, 1999</ref> With [[Sid Bass]] and [[Lee Bass]], two billionaires from [[Fort Worth, Texas]], he developed the new community.<ref name=\"julietamaki\"/> The project cost US $5 billion.<ref name=\"julietamaki\"/>\n\nThe lake was built on top of the [[Las Vegas Wash]], which continues to flow under the lake in two {{convert|96|in|m|adj=mid|}} diameter pipes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvwash.org/wash/wash_images/wtour10.html |title=Wash Tour |accessdate=2008-01-13 |work=[[Las Vegas Wash Project Coordination Team]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411150354/http://www.lvwash.org/wash/wash_images/wtour10.html |archivedate=2008-04-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Water diversion to fill the lake began in 1990.<ref name=llvr1>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakelasvegas.com/aboutus_timeline.asp |title=LAKE LAS VEGAS RESORT TIMELINE |accessdate=2008-01-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229223935/http://www.lakelasvegas.com/aboutus_timeline.asp |archivedate=2007-12-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The lake was filled with {{convert|3|e9USgal|e6m3|abbr=unit}} of water.<ref name=RJ2080802/>\n\nLake at Las Vegas Joint Venture, LLC filed for [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] on July 17, 2008. Debts were estimated at between $500 million and $1 billion.<ref name=ktnv1>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Lake Las Vegas Filed For Chapter 11 |url=http://www.ktnv.com/global/story.asp?s=8695859 |work= |publisher=[[KTNV]] |date=2008-07-17 |accessdate=2008-07-17 }}</ref>\n\nLake Las Vegas emerged from bankruptcy in July 2010 with a plan that took nearly two years to complete.  All existing debt was wiped away and the development has $30 million in hand to complete several of the unfinished infrastructure projects.  The Lake Las Vegas bankruptcy creditors, not Lake Las Vegas development themselves, have filed a lawsuit against the former insiders (Bass Brothers, TransContinental, etc.). The creditors' theory is that the $500 million equity loan the former insiders took against the property caused the demise of Lake Las Vegas.  The creditors are hoping to recoup money from the former insiders.  In a related action, resort property owners are suing lender [[Credit Suisse#2000s|Credit Suisse]] as part of a multibillion-dollar lawsuit led by bankrupt [[Yellowstone Club]] founder [[Tim Blixseth|Timothy Blixseth]] and his son Beau Blixseth who claim the Lake Las Vegas Joint Venture bankruptcy was caused by a \"loan to own\" scheme between the bank and resort developers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703580904574638052691063912 |title=Luxury-Property Owners Sue Credit Suisse for $24 Billion|first=Jaqueline |last=Palank |work=The Wall Street Journal |date= January 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe golf course was purchased by Nevada South Shore LLC, a Hawaii-based corporation for $4.5 million on February 17, 2011.<ref name=lvs20110401/>\n\nThe Ritz Carlton, Lake Las Vegas, closed after 8 years of operation on  May 2, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ritz-Carlton Lake Las Vegas to close in May|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/feb/08/ritz-carlton-lake-las-vegas/|first=Amanda|last=Finnegan|date=February 8, 2010|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]}}</ref>  The Ritz Carlton was then reopened by international boutique hotelier Dolce Hotels on February 11, 2011, as the Ravella at Lake Las Vegas.<ref name=lvs20110401>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Takahashi |title= New hotel banks on Lake Las Vegas bouncing back |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/feb/11/lake-las-vegas/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=Feb 11, 2011 |accessdate=2011-03-11 }}</ref> On April 30, 2013, Kam Sang Co. announced that the Ravella would be renamed the Hilton Lake Las Vegas, the name under which the hotel continues to operate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2013/apr/30/lake-las-vegas-hotel-getting-new-name-again/#/0|title=Lake Las Vegas hotel getting new name \u2014 again|first=Eli|last=Segall|publisher=Vegas Inc|date=April 30, 2013}}</ref> The Hilton opened June 6, 2013.<ref>{{cite press|title=Hilton Hotels & Resorts Makes Lake Las Vegas Debut|publisher=Hilton Hotels & Resorts|date=June 6, 2013|url=http://news.hilton.com/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/23369}}</ref>\n\nLake Las Vegas was the subject of a lawsuit between investment fund Claymore Holdings and [[Credit Suisse]], which was the agent for a syndicate of entities that loaned $540 million to develop the property. Claymore and others accused Credit Suisse of fraudulently inflating the value of the development in order to generate higher fees for itself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Checkler|first1=Joseph|last2=Fitzgerald|first2=Patrick|title=Emails About Loans Plague Credit Suisse|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/emails-about-precrisis-loans-plague-credit-suisse-1417561282|accessdate=5 December 2014|newspaper=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> The core of the allegations centered on a new appraisal methodology conceived of by Credit Suisse executive David Miller, who in internal emails is referred to as Credit Suisse's Dr. Frankenstein.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Celarier|first1=Michelle|title=Hedge fund giant claims Suisse\u2019s appraisals full of holes|url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/03/hedge-fund-giant-claims-suisses-appraisals-full-of-holes/|accessdate=5 December 2014|newspaper=New York Post}}</ref> In 2015, a Texas judge ordered Credit Suisse to pay $288 million to Highland, Claymore and others.  The verdict was partially offset by other payments to Highland, meaning that Claymore received most of the Credit Suisse judgment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/699975/highland-gets-288m-from-credit-suisse-for-land-deal-fraud|title=Highland Gets $288M From Credit Suisse For Land Deal Fraud - Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref>  That Judgment was reversed by the Texas Supreme Court in April 2020, and Claymore's Judgment was reduced to 40 million (plus interest).  <ref>{{https://www.txcourts.gov/media/1446454/180403.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Casino MonteLago/Lake Las Vegas Event Center==\n{{Infobox casino\n| name          = Casino MonteLago/Lake Las Vegas Event Center\n| logo          = \n| logo_size     = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| image_caption = \n| location      = [[Henderson, Nevada]]\n| address       = 8 Strada di Villaggio\n| date_opened   = May 8, 2003\n| names_pre     = \n| date_closed   = October 29, 2013\n| casino_type   = Land-based\n| theme         = [[Europe]]an\n| owner         = Kam Sang Co.\n| license_holder= Intrepid Gaming\n| architect     = \n| rooms         = \n| space_gaming  = {{convert|40000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| shows         = \n| attractions   = \n| notable_restaurants   = \n| renovations   = 2011\n| website       = \n}}\n'''Casino MonteLago''' was opened on May 8, 2003, having been built by [[Cook Inlet Region, Inc.]], an Alaska Native shareholder owned corporation.<ref>{{cite news |title=License sought to operate shuttered Casino MonteLago |first=Amanda |last=Finnegan |url=http://m.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/apr/01/license-sought-operate-shuttered-casino-montelago/ |newspaper= [[Las Vegas Sun]]|date=April 1, 2011 |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> The casino closed for the first time on March 14, 2010, due to the [[Great Recession]];<ref>{{cite news |title=Casino MonteLago at Lake Las Vegas to close next month |first=Amanda |last=Finnegan|newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=February 16, 2010 |url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/feb/16/casino-montelago-lake-las-vegas-close-next-month/|accessdate= September 22, 2010}}</ref> but on May 26, 2011, after renovation, the casino re-opened to the public.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casino MonteLago reopens at Lake Las Vegas|first=Liz|last=Benson|date=May 26, 2011|url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2011/may/26/casino-montelago-reopens-lake-las-vegas/|publisher=Vegas Inc}}</ref> In November 2012, the casino was acquired along with the Ravella at Lake Las Vegas for a total of $47 million by Kam Sang Co., a California-based real estate developer.<ref>{{cite news|title=California company buys Ravella, Casino MonteLago for $46.8 million|first=Buck|last=Wargo|newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-11-29|url=http://www.lvrj.com/business/california-company-buys-ravella-casino-montelago-for-46-8-million-181419401.html}}</ref> The casino closed for the second time on October 29, 2013, as a result of a lease dispute between Kam Sang and the casino's operators.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casino MonteLago at Lake Las Vegas closes over lease issues|newspaper=Vegas Inc|first=Eli |last=Segall|date=October 29, 2013|url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2013/oct/29/casino-montelago-lake-las-vegas-closes-over-lease-/|accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref> In the beginning of 2016, the facility reopened as the Lake Las Vegas Event Center, hosting special events, exhibits and entertainment. It is attached to the Hilton Lake Las Vegas and accessible from MonteLago Village.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.reviewjournal.com/real-estate-millions/lake-las-vegas-starts-comeback-great-recession|title = Lake Las Vegas starts comeback from Great Recession|date = June 28, 2015|accessdate = September 6, 2015|website = Las Vegas Review-Journal|publisher = Las Vegas Review-Journal|last = Thilmont|first = Greg}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite news|title=Lake Las Vegas emerging from bankruptcy protection|publisher=Associated Press|date=July 19, 2010|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9H26QE87.htm}}\n* {{cite news|title=Lake Las Vegas emerges from bankruptcy|first=Steve|last=Green|date=July 16, 2010|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/jul/16/lake-las-vegas/|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]}}\n* {{cite news|title=Company plans to rebrand closed Ritz-Carlton at Lake Las Vegas|first=Steve|last=Green|date=September 21, 2010|url=http://m.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/sep/21/company-plans-rebrand-closed-ritz-carlton-lake-las/|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://llvsportsclub.com Lake Las Vegas Sports Club]\n*[http://www.essenceandherbs.com Essence & Herbs]\n*[http://www.lakelasvegas.com/ Lake Las Vegas]\n*[http://www.lakelasvegasnv.org Lake Las Vegas Blog]\n*[http://lunarossalakelv.com Luna Rossa Ristorante]\n*[http://www.marssalasvegas.com Marssa]\n*Roth, David. \"[http://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Articles/2011/07/21/The-5-Worst-Places-to-Retire-in-the-US.aspx#page1 The Fiscal Times].\" ''[[The Fiscal Times]]''. July 21, 2011.\n*[http://www.sonrisagrill.com Sonrisa Grill]\n*[http://www.sunsetvines.com/ Sunset & Vines]\n\n{{Las Vegas Valley}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Nevada|Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Clark County, Nevada|Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Planned communities in Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Triathlon venues]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox body of water\n | name = Lake Las Vegas\n | image = Lake Las Vegas aerial view.jpg\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry =\n | caption_bathymetry =\n | location = [[Henderson, Nevada]]\n | type = [[Artificial lake]]\n | inflow = \n | outflow = Las Vegas Wash\n | catchment = nil\n | basin_countries = United States\n | length =\n | width =\n | area = {{convert|320|acre|abbr=on}}\n | depth =\n | max-depth =\n | volume =\n | residence_time =\n | shore = {{convert|10|mi|abbr=on}}\n | elevation = {{convert|1400|ft|abbr=on}}\n | islands = 0\n | cities = Lake Las Vegas\n | frozen =\n | reference = <ref name=lvl1>{{cite news |first=Scott |last= Dickensheets |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Is Lake Las Vegas Half Full or Half Empty? |work= [[Las Vegas Life]] |publisher= |date=November 2000 }}</ref>\n |coordinates = {{coord|36|06|07.2|N|114|55|46.2|W|display=inline}}\n |pushpin_map             = USA Nevada\n |pushpin_label_position  = \n |pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Nevada\n}}\n[[File:Lake Las Vegas 1.jpg|thumb|240px|Lake Las Vegas in 2007]]\n\n'''Lake Las Vegas''' in [[Henderson, Nevada]], refers to a {{convert|320|acre|adj=on}} [[artificial lake]] and the {{convert|3592|acre|adj=on}} developed area around the lake.<ref name=rj1/><ref name=iht1/>  The area is sometimes referred to as the ''Lake Las Vegas Resort''. It is being developed by 5 companies including Lake at Las Vegas Joint Venture LLC.<ref name=ktnv1/>\n\nThe area includes three resorts including the Aston MonteLago Village Resort, the Westin Lake Las Vegas Resort, and the Hilton Lake Las Vegas.\n\nThe dam that creates the lake is \"an earthen structure 18 stories high, {{convert|4800|ft|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|716|ft|abbr=on}} wide at its base. It contains roughly the same amount of dirt as [[Hoover Dam]] does concrete,\"<ref name=lvl1/> and was completed in 1991.<ref name=llvr1/>  The [[Las Vegas Wash]] passes under the lake and dam in pipes that require maintenance every 10 years.<ref name=RJ2080802>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= EDITORIAL: Lake Las Vegas -- dry? |url=http://www.lvrj.com/opinion/26204144.html |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |publisher= |date= 2008-08-02|accessdate=2008-08-02 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nActor [[J. Carlton Adair]] conceived Lake Las Vegas around 1967 as ''Lake Adair''. At the time he purchased the land and water rights. In 1987, [[Ronald Boeddeker]] acquired {{convert|2000|acre|abbr=on}} from the US Government when Adair went bankrupt.<ref name=rj1>{{cite news|title=Lake Las Vegas properties change hands|last=Knightly |first=Arnold M.|date=2008-01-09|accessdate = 2008-01-13|pages=1D, 4D|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/lake-las-vegas-properties-change-hands}}</ref><ref name=iht1>{{cite news|title=Lakeside resort trumps Las Vegas | url= http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/01/09/america/relake.php |last= Vaucher|first=Andr\u00e9a R.|date=2008-01-10|accessdate = 2008-01-13|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nThe property was acquired by Transcontinental Properties in 1990. In 1995, [[Henry Gluck]], the former chairman and chief executive officer of [[Caesars World]], became the co-Chairman of Transcontinental Properties.<ref name=\"julietamaki\">Julie Tamaki, [http://articles.latimes.com/1999/aug/01/realestate/re-61511 Viva Luxe Vegas], ''The Los Angeles Times'', August 01, 1999</ref> With [[Sid Bass]] and [[Lee Bass]], two billionaires from [[Fort Worth, Texas]], he developed the new community.<ref name=\"julietamaki\"/> The project cost US $5 billion.<ref name=\"julietamaki\"/>\n\nThe lake was built on top of the [[Las Vegas Wash]], which continues to flow under the lake in two {{convert|96|in|m|adj=mid|}} diameter pipes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvwash.org/wash/wash_images/wtour10.html |title=Wash Tour |accessdate=2008-01-13 |work=[[Las Vegas Wash Project Coordination Team]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411150354/http://www.lvwash.org/wash/wash_images/wtour10.html |archivedate=2008-04-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Water diversion to fill the lake began in 1990.<ref name=llvr1>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakelasvegas.com/aboutus_timeline.asp |title=LAKE LAS VEGAS RESORT TIMELINE |accessdate=2008-01-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229223935/http://www.lakelasvegas.com/aboutus_timeline.asp |archivedate=2007-12-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The lake was filled with {{convert|3|e9USgal|e6m3|abbr=unit}} of water.<ref name=RJ2080802/>\n\nLake at Las Vegas Joint Venture, LLC filed for [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] on July 17, 2008. Debts were estimated at between $500 million and $1 billion.<ref name=ktnv1>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Lake Las Vegas Filed For Chapter 11 |url=http://www.ktnv.com/global/story.asp?s=8695859 |work= |publisher=[[KTNV]] |date=2008-07-17 |accessdate=2008-07-17 }}</ref>\n\nLake Las Vegas emerged from bankruptcy in July 2010 with a plan that took nearly two years to complete.  All existing debt was wiped away and the development has $30 million in hand to complete several of the unfinished infrastructure projects.  The Lake Las Vegas bankruptcy creditors, not Lake Las Vegas development themselves, have filed a lawsuit against the former insiders (Bass Brothers, TransContinental, etc.). The creditors' theory is that the $500 million equity loan the former insiders took against the property caused the demise of Lake Las Vegas.  The creditors are hoping to recoup money from the former insiders.  In a related action, resort property owners are suing lender [[Credit Suisse#2000s|Credit Suisse]] as part of a multibillion-dollar lawsuit led by bankrupt [[Yellowstone Club]] founder [[Tim Blixseth|Timothy Blixseth]] and his son Beau Blixseth who claim the Lake Las Vegas Joint Venture bankruptcy was caused by a \"loan to own\" scheme between the bank and resort developers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703580904574638052691063912 |title=Luxury-Property Owners Sue Credit Suisse for $24 Billion|first=Jaqueline |last=Palank |work=The Wall Street Journal |date= January 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe golf course was purchased by Nevada South Shore LLC, a Hawaii-based corporation for $4.5 million on February 17, 2011.<ref name=lvs20110401/>\n\nThe Ritz Carlton, Lake Las Vegas, closed after 8 years of operation on  May 2, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ritz-Carlton Lake Las Vegas to close in May|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/feb/08/ritz-carlton-lake-las-vegas/|first=Amanda|last=Finnegan|date=February 8, 2010|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]}}</ref>  The Ritz Carlton was then reopened by international boutique hotelier Dolce Hotels on February 11, 2011, as the Ravella at Lake Las Vegas.<ref name=lvs20110401>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Takahashi |title= New hotel banks on Lake Las Vegas bouncing back |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/feb/11/lake-las-vegas/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=Feb 11, 2011 |accessdate=2011-03-11 }}</ref> On April 30, 2013, Kam Sang Co. announced that the Ravella would be renamed the Hilton Lake Las Vegas, the name under which the hotel continues to operate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2013/apr/30/lake-las-vegas-hotel-getting-new-name-again/#/0|title=Lake Las Vegas hotel getting new name \u2014 again|first=Eli|last=Segall|publisher=Vegas Inc|date=April 30, 2013}}</ref> The Hilton opened June 6, 2013.<ref>{{cite press|title=Hilton Hotels & Resorts Makes Lake Las Vegas Debut|publisher=Hilton Hotels & Resorts|date=June 6, 2013|url=http://news.hilton.com/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/23369}}</ref>\n\nLake Las Vegas was the subject of a lawsuit between investment fund Claymore Holdings and [[Credit Suisse]], which was the agent for a syndicate of entities that loaned $540 million to develop the property. Claymore and others accused Credit Suisse of fraudulently inflating the value of the development in order to generate higher fees for itself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Checkler|first1=Joseph|last2=Fitzgerald|first2=Patrick|title=Emails About Loans Plague Credit Suisse|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/emails-about-precrisis-loans-plague-credit-suisse-1417561282|accessdate=5 December 2014|newspaper=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> The core of the allegations centered on a new appraisal methodology conceived of by Credit Suisse executive David Miller, who in internal emails is referred to as Credit Suisse's Dr. Frankenstein.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Celarier|first1=Michelle|title=Hedge fund giant claims Suisse\u2019s appraisals full of holes|url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/03/hedge-fund-giant-claims-suisses-appraisals-full-of-holes/|accessdate=5 December 2014|newspaper=New York Post}}</ref> In 2015, a Texas judge ordered Credit Suisse to pay $288 million to Highland, Claymore and others.  The verdict was partially offset by other payments to Highland, meaning that Claymore received most of the Credit Suisse judgment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/699975/highland-gets-288m-from-credit-suisse-for-land-deal-fraud|title=Highland Gets $288M From Credit Suisse For Land Deal Fraud - Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref>  That Judgment was reversed by the Texas Supreme Court in April 2020, and Claymore's Judgment was reduced to 40 million (plus interest).  <ref> https://www.txcourts.gov/media/1446454/180403.pdf\n\n== Casino MonteLago/Lake Las Vegas Event Center==\n{{Infobox casino\n| name          = Casino MonteLago/Lake Las Vegas Event Center\n| logo          = \n| logo_size     = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| image_caption = \n| location      = [[Henderson, Nevada]]\n| address       = 8 Strada di Villaggio\n| date_opened   = May 8, 2003\n| names_pre     = \n| date_closed   = October 29, 2013\n| casino_type   = Land-based\n| theme         = [[Europe]]an\n| owner         = Kam Sang Co.\n| license_holder= Intrepid Gaming\n| architect     = \n| rooms         = \n| space_gaming  = {{convert|40000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| shows         = \n| attractions   = \n| notable_restaurants   = \n| renovations   = 2011\n| website       = \n}}\n'''Casino MonteLago''' was opened on May 8, 2003, having been built by [[Cook Inlet Region, Inc.]], an Alaska Native shareholder owned corporation.<ref>{{cite news |title=License sought to operate shuttered Casino MonteLago |first=Amanda |last=Finnegan |url=http://m.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/apr/01/license-sought-operate-shuttered-casino-montelago/ |newspaper= [[Las Vegas Sun]]|date=April 1, 2011 |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> The casino closed for the first time on March 14, 2010, due to the [[Great Recession]];<ref>{{cite news |title=Casino MonteLago at Lake Las Vegas to close next month |first=Amanda |last=Finnegan|newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=February 16, 2010 |url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/feb/16/casino-montelago-lake-las-vegas-close-next-month/|accessdate= September 22, 2010}}</ref> but on May 26, 2011, after renovation, the casino re-opened to the public.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casino MonteLago reopens at Lake Las Vegas|first=Liz|last=Benson|date=May 26, 2011|url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2011/may/26/casino-montelago-reopens-lake-las-vegas/|publisher=Vegas Inc}}</ref> In November 2012, the casino was acquired along with the Ravella at Lake Las Vegas for a total of $47 million by Kam Sang Co., a California-based real estate developer.<ref>{{cite news|title=California company buys Ravella, Casino MonteLago for $46.8 million|first=Buck|last=Wargo|newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-11-29|url=http://www.lvrj.com/business/california-company-buys-ravella-casino-montelago-for-46-8-million-181419401.html}}</ref> The casino closed for the second time on October 29, 2013, as a result of a lease dispute between Kam Sang and the casino's operators.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casino MonteLago at Lake Las Vegas closes over lease issues|newspaper=Vegas Inc|first=Eli |last=Segall|date=October 29, 2013|url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2013/oct/29/casino-montelago-lake-las-vegas-closes-over-lease-/|accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref> In the beginning of 2016, the facility reopened as the Lake Las Vegas Event Center, hosting special events, exhibits and entertainment. It is attached to the Hilton Lake Las Vegas and accessible from MonteLago Village.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.reviewjournal.com/real-estate-millions/lake-las-vegas-starts-comeback-great-recession|title = Lake Las Vegas starts comeback from Great Recession|date = June 28, 2015|accessdate = September 6, 2015|website = Las Vegas Review-Journal|publisher = Las Vegas Review-Journal|last = Thilmont|first = Greg}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite news|title=Lake Las Vegas emerging from bankruptcy protection|publisher=Associated Press|date=July 19, 2010|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9H26QE87.htm}}\n* {{cite news|title=Lake Las Vegas emerges from bankruptcy|first=Steve|last=Green|date=July 16, 2010|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/jul/16/lake-las-vegas/|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]}}\n* {{cite news|title=Company plans to rebrand closed Ritz-Carlton at Lake Las Vegas|first=Steve|last=Green|date=September 21, 2010|url=http://m.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/sep/21/company-plans-rebrand-closed-ritz-carlton-lake-las/|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://llvsportsclub.com Lake Las Vegas Sports Club]\n*[http://www.essenceandherbs.com Essence & Herbs]\n*[http://www.lakelasvegas.com/ Lake Las Vegas]\n*[http://www.lakelasvegasnv.org Lake Las Vegas Blog]\n*[http://lunarossalakelv.com Luna Rossa Ristorante]\n*[http://www.marssalasvegas.com Marssa]\n*Roth, David. \"[http://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Articles/2011/07/21/The-5-Worst-Places-to-Retire-in-the-US.aspx#page1 The Fiscal Times].\" ''[[The Fiscal Times]]''. July 21, 2011.\n*[http://www.sonrisagrill.com Sonrisa Grill]\n*[http://www.sunsetvines.com/ Sunset & Vines]\n\n{{Las Vegas Valley}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Nevada|Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Clark County, Nevada|Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Planned communities in Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Triathlon venues]]\n", "name_user": "Pmd669", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Las_Vegas"}
